<dl id="un1005t"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1005">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un1all.htm#un1005t"> (NLI.3) 5(t)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Crabbe (Geo): Borough</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The other revenant, <mark>GEORGE CRABBE</mark>, did better. After a silence almost unbroken for two-and-twenty years, he resumed his sturdy rhyming in 1807, and in 1810 enriched the language with a poem of really solid merit, the <mark><cite>Borough</cite></mark>, a picture of social and physical conditions in a seaside town on the Eastern Coast. Crabbe never excelled, perhaps never equalled, this saturnine study of the miseries of provincial life; like his own watchman, the poet seems to have no other design than to "let in truth, terror, and the day." <small> Edmund Gosse, <a name="EGSH" href="/udra/udex.htm#EGSH"><cite title="source">A Short History of Modern English Literature</cite></a> (1897), 319</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: George Crabbe (1754-1832), English poet. </mm> </dd></dl>
